An inspector may issue three types of notices to both companies and individuals, depending on the type of work health and safety duty that the inspector believes has been breached. These are:

improvement notices

prohibition notices

non-disturbance notices

 

 

An inspector can issue an improvement notice if he or she believes that a person is breaching WHS laws and circumstances suggest that the person will continue to do so. The improvement notice may direct measures to be taken to fix the contravention or to prevent a further contravention from occurring.

 

For example, an improvement notice may require a PCBU to remove blockages to emergency exits even if no health and safety incidents have occurred. Inspectors may also require that a new WHS policy be implemented if they believe the current policy is inadequate.

 

A person must comply with a notice within the specified period unless an extension has been sought. An individual who fails to comply with an improvement notice faces a maximum penalty of $50,000. A corporation faces a maximum penalty of $250,000.

 

(Victoria: $75,835)
